  "doc_id": "35002",
  "text": "Five studies utilized the irritable bowel syndrome quality of life instrument (IBS-QOL) as a secondary outcome and of these, 80.0% ( = 4) reported a significant improvement at end-of-intervention. Between the end-of-intervention and the follow-up assessment, significant further improvement was seen in two of these studies while the other two studies showed maintenance of improvement. One study demonstrated a significant improvement in IBS-QOL in both the intervention group and the wait list control group that was maintained at follow-up [CITATION_1] . The study reporting long-term follow-up data only showed maintenance of QOL improvement. The study that enrolled IBD patients used an objective biomarker for the assessment of intestinal inflammation [CITATION_2] ; Evidence-Based Complementary and Alternative Medicine however none of the other studies used objective tests for the assessment of FGID symptoms as primary or secondary outcome measures. All of the assessment tools relied on validated patient/self-report outcome measures. Two studies [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] used a linear mixed-effects model to observe the difference in rates of change between the MBT and control intervention over time amid significant interaction effects between group and time were seen ( < 001).",
